While scanning a repository, FishEye makes calls to the version control system client (e.g. {{git}} or {{hg}}) and passes filenames, branch names and tag names as command line arguments. On Windows, there is a known [bug|http://bugs.sun.com/bugdatabase/view_bug.do?bug_id=4947220] in the Sun JVM that causes unicode characters (that are not part of the [1252 codepage|http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows-1252]) in command line arguments to be replaced by {{'?'}} characters.

This typically results in errors like:

{noformat}
java.lang.Exception: Problem with slurp - Repository index failed due to error - 
class com.atlassian.fisheye.dvcs.handler.DvcsProcessException: 
Error while communicating with VCS: ????c????????e??oa?a: No such file in rev 8de7550ee45b
{noformat}

In the Sun bug report a workaround is suggested using environment variables instead of command line arguments but that does not seem to work either.

This issue does not affect Subversion and CVS, as FishEye does not use the command line client when scanning the repository.

A workaround for this issue is to run FishEye on a different operating system.

With Clearcase, the Lucene index corresponding to the diff text (added and removed lines per changeset and per file) is not populated.

{quote}
For a given repository {{myrepo}}, this index can be found inside the {{var}} folder, at {{/var/cache/myrepo/idx2}}.
{quote}

The issue is that, with the new search, the lack of results for the diff texts is very visible, since it is one of the category of results with its own counter. For a ClearCase repository, this counter is always zero and its result page is always empty.

Fisheye has clever detection of insignificant whitespace. It would be awesome if it also understood leading //'s for comment lines.

That is, if I have a change where I comment out the following method:
{noformat}
public void foo()
{
    doStuff();
}
{noformat}
{noformat}
// public void foo()
// {
//     doStuff();
// }
{noformat}

or vice versa, then fisheye should figure out that I haven't deleted 5 lines and added 5 other ones, but just added some "// "s to the start of the lines.

Our internal parser looks for output in out felog extension looking like:
{code}
M: commit message
P: PARENTCOMMITHASH
{code}

If we see a commit message like this
{code}
M: Commit Message
P:
P: PARENTCOMMITHASH
{code}
Our parser fails, expecting to see a F: line instead of another P: line

We should change our parser look for a different commit message terminator that will not occur (or is less likely to occur) in a commit message itself.

The error will look like:
{code}
Error

Repository index failed due to error com.cenqua.fisheye.rep.RepositoryClientException: com.atlassian.fisheye.dvcs.handler.DvcsProcessException: Error while communicating with VCS: extension 'felog' overrides commands: fecheck felog feparents com.atlassian.fisheye.dvcs.handler.DvcsProcessException: Error while communicating with VCS: extension 'felog' overrides commands: fecheck felog feparents com.atlassian.utils.process.ProcessException: While executing: "hg --config extensions.felog=/Users/mwatson/work/crucible/fisheye/output/dist/python/hg/hgfelog/hgfelog.py --config ui.verbose=false felog 7267310cf0ec8eb5bc90b33a6a88bf55b9158649 -p -m " com.atlassian.utils.process.ProcessException: java.lang.RuntimeException: Match failed: string [P:cb317ce5428875d2da371a55b11ba610ab68807a], pattern [F:(.*)] java.lang.RuntimeException: Match failed: string [P:cb317ce5428875d2da371a55b11ba610ab68807a], pattern [F:(.*)]{code}

If a file is located at:
{code}
/src/main/java/file.java 
{code}

Searching for "file.java", works. However, searching for "java/file.java" does not resturn results.

Our [Docs|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/FISHEYE/Searching+the+Repository] describe more complex situations that work.

The concrete use case to be solved by this issue is to enable fast retrieval of change sets "linked" to a given set of JIRA issues.

We rely on this linking for release processes, and so enforce both the presence and format of the link. In our case the link is the JIRA issue key placed at the very beginning of the commit message.

Fisheye currently supports searching the full text index for a "word", or using a regex. Both of these methods can retrieve changesets based on a JIRA issue key in the commit message, but the first is too imprecise (picking up issue keys not at the beginning) and both are too slow. I would like to be able to retrieve the linked changesets for 100s of JIRA issues in a matter of seconds.

So to the proposal:

Fisheye could support adding user fields to the index, based on a regular expression. For example:

{code}
 keyName=>user:MyLinkFormat , expression=>^[A-Z]+-\d+ , field=>comment
{code}

Then when indexing the repository, the comment (or source, or whatever) is searched for matches, and added to the index using the specified key.

This should then be available in EyeQL:

{code}
 select revisions from dir / where user:MyLinkFormat = "JIRA-1234"
{code}

